data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3.4+ supports generic `DynamicData<T1, T2, ...>` with tuples, giving you compile-time type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<string, bool>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key changes:**
- `DynamicData` → `DynamicData<string, bool>` — type params match the test method signature
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — tuples instead of object arrays
- `["valid@email.com", true]` → `("valid@email.com", true)` — tuple syntax

This catches type mismatches at compile time rather than runtime. Requires **MSTest 3.4+** (`Microsoft.Testing.Framework`).
